Overall this approach looks good to me.
typo: extra space or should there be a number here?
This comment got completely removed and replaced with a better comment about how it works.

Hmm... I just realized: Does this `timestamp + index` approach for the ID still work after this change?

For example, if I have these timestamps in the journal:
A. 100
B. 101
C. 101
D. 101
E. 102

When I read them all, I get these IDs:
A. 100
B. 101
C. 101_2
D. 101_3
E. 102

If I skip to C, with the more efficient reads, won't I get these IDs because I skipped getting the timestamp for the first 101 entry:
C. 101
D. 101_2
E. 102

Would changing to something like `timestamp + sequence number` help avoid this?

yep.  that’s a good catch.  I tested a lot of cases, but didn’t test that one.

I posted a script to openbmc-tools to test this.
Don't we want the zero-based index for journal access?

We do, but in the way sd_journal_next_skip works, we need to skip at least one entry.

FWIW, when I found this, I thought it was weird too.... but it gives the right behavior.
Acknowledged

I remembered a little about what the deal is here;  sd_journal_seek_monotonic_usec seeks to the entry, but documents that you always have to call sd_journal_next* to resolve the entry after you've seeked.

sd_journal_next_skip(..., 0);

Doesn't move the pointer at all, and is basically noop in our case:

https://github.com/systemd/systemd/blob/e8468541727db9cea18cf29c39f46013bce1bae3/src/libsystemd/sd-journal/sd-journal.c#L1135

Because that this point we have locationType LOCATION_SEEK.

Adding 1 to it makes the tests pass, including for the non zero case, so I think it's counting the seek pointer as one of the things to skip.

This is different behavior than when your seek is already on an entry.
Acknowledged
